---
description: Prefer a single destructured options object over multiple positional parameters
globs: **/*.{ts,tsx}
alwaysApply: false
---

# Prefer Destructured Params

When a function takes more than one argument, accept a single object and
destructure it. Positional args (especially trailing optional callbacks) force
the reader to jump to the definition to learn what each value means; named
fields make the call site self-documenting.

- Two or more params → take one options object and destructure it.
- A single, obvious param (e.g. `hasAllowance(amount)`) can stay positional.
- Keep the source's property names at the call site (see
  `no-rename-on-destructure`).

```ts
// ❌ BAD — positional args, unclear at the call site
async function lock(amount: bigint, onHash?: (h: Hex) => void, onSendId?: (s: Hex) => void) {}
await lock(parsed, actions.setLockHash, actions.setSendId);

// ✅ GOOD — named fields, self-documenting
async function lock({ amount, onHash, onSendId }: {
  amount: bigint;
  onHash?: (h: Hex) => void;
  onSendId?: (s: Hex) => void;
}) {}
await lock({ amount: parsed, onHash: actions.setLockHash, onSendId: actions.setSendId });
```
